what i wrote:
Even as a young child, I‚Äôve always enjoyed the theoretical idea of parallel worlds ‚Äî infinite possibilities, infinite fates. Naturally, when a ‚ÄúVeritasium‚Äù video introduced this idea in relation to quantum physics and Schr√∂dinger's cat, I was taken away. This video brought me back to a vivid childhood memory of sitting in the local Explorit Center, mesmerized by an exhibit that demonstrated the nature of particles at the quantum level. Though 6-year-old me knew nothing about the physics and mathematics behind the dancing dots, this experience planted the seed for my interest in quantum physics. 

The more I learned about quantum physics through online articles and videos, the more I realized it conflicted with a naive belief I always held: the more something is broken down, the simpler it gets. This inconsistency has deepened my interest and yearning to learn. I hope to unravel many of the questions I have through attending PHYSICS 13N.

As Software Robot Lead of my world-class FIRST Robotics Competition team (1678 Citrus Circuits) and a member of the software subteam since my freshman year, I‚Äôve experienced first hand the importance of efficiency in a system, from both a code and electronics point of view. I‚Äôve already worked intensively on the software side of the story, incorporating multithreading into our code architecture to work around latent hardware devices. Over time, I became increasingly interested in how the hardware end functioned and collected the various data values.

My robotics experience has shown me how closely intertwined hardware and software are. One of my biggest goals at Stanford is to deepen my robotics career and explore automated machines. Learning about cutting edge quantum sensors and other breakthroughs through PHYSICS 13N will greatly complement this journey.

the program description:
What is quantum physics and what makes it so weird? We'll introduce key aspects of quantum physics with an aim to explain why it differs from everyday "classical" physics.  Quantum-enabled devices like the laser and atomic clocks for GPS will be explained. We will also discuss the breakthroughs driving the 2nd quantum technology revolution surrounding quantum simulators, sensors, and computers. Seminar discussions and a laser lab will help illustrate core principles, including the atomic clock mechanism. Visits to campus laboratories will introduce cutting-edge quantum experiments.

This IntroSem is designed for those likely to go on to major in the humanities or in a STEM program outside of the natural sciences. (Likely STEM majors are instead encouraged to take 100-level quantum courses upon completion of pre-requirements.) While basic familiarity with high school physics is recommended, qualitative explanations will be emphasized. By the end of the quarter, you will be able to explain the key tenets of quantum physics, how it has enabled current technology, and what new technologies might emerge from the 2nd quantum revolution.
